<paragraph blockId="86.[189,1399,333,465]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis allCaps="true" box="[189,286,333,359]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">COLOUR.</emphasis>
Mostly bright orange, except as follows: frontal vitta velvety black, except for partially orange ocellar triangle, contrasting with pale frons; face, parafacial, gena and postgena pale yellow-white. Fore tibia black with apex narrowly yellow, fore tarsus bright yellow; hind and mid tarsi brown. Hind femur with a broad, indistinct black band just beyond base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="86.[189,1399,504,636]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis allCaps="true" box="[189,259,504,530]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">HEAD.</emphasis>
Frontal vitta characteristically shaped, with anterior portion broadly tapered and widely separated from very pale frontal margin (continuous with anterior margin in the similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Marshall, 2019" authorityName="Marshall" authorityYear="2019" box="[1078,1178,540,565]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Mesoconius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="garyi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1078,1178,540,565]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">M. garyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1183,1275,540,566]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
), posterior portion elongate triangular; broadest part of vitta continuous with a narrow transverse black band almost meeting eye.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="86.[189,1406,675,771]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis allCaps="true" box="[189,287,675,701]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">THORAX.</emphasis>
Scutellum with long, thin apical bristles. Vertical row of katepisternal bristles golden. Katatergite not swollen, without median process, evenly convex and microtrichose. Wing entirely yellowish, without clear bands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="86.[189,1398,811,872]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis allCaps="true" box="[189,306,811,837]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">ABDOMEN.</emphasis>
Strongly petiolate, T1+2 darker than and twice as long as T3, basally narrow, with a strong constriction between T1 and T2, apically as wide as base of T3.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="86" pageNumber="87" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="86.[189,303,912,938]" box="[189,303,912,938]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,912,938]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,912,938]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="86.[189,1399,958,1230]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
<bibRefCitation accessDate="2019-07-23" author="Enderlein" box="[189,386,958,984]" firstAuthor="Enderlein" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fur Naturgeschichte A" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" pagination="140 - 229" part="88" publicationUrl="https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/45506103" refId="ref59018" refString="Enderlein G. 1922. Klassifikation der Micropeziden. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte A 88 (5): 140 - 229. Available from https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 45506103 [accessed 23 Jul. 2019]." title="Klassifikation der Micropeziden" type="journal article" year="1922">Enderlein (1922)</bibRefCitation>
named two similar orange species, both collected by Otto Garlepp, as ʻ 
<taxonomicName authority="Schiner, 1864" authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1922" box="[1205,1304,958,984]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Tanypoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="garleppi">
<emphasis box="[1205,1304,958,984]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">garleppi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ʼ, one in the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Schiner, 1864" authorityName="Schiner" authorityYear="1864" box="[306,421,993,1019]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Tanypoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[306,421,993,1019]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Tanypoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and one in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[669,809,994,1019]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Mesoconius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[669,809,994,1019]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Mesoconius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Schiner, 1864" authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1922" box="[823,1043,993,1019]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Tanypoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="garleppi">
<emphasis box="[823,1043,993,1019]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Tanypoda garleppi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was later moved to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1927" box="[1275,1399,993,1019]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Aristobata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1275,1399,993,1019]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Aristobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hennig" box="[228,403,1028,1055]" firstAuthor="Hennig" journalOrPublisher="Stettiner Entomologische Zeitung" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" pagination="27 - 67" part="96" refId="ref59213" refString="Hennig W. 1935. Revision der Tyliden (Dipt., Acalypt.). I. Teil: Die Taeniapterinae Amerikas [conclusion]. Stettiner Entomologische Zeitung 96: 27 - 67." title="Revision der Tyliden (Dipt., Acalypt.). I. Teil: Die Taeniapterinae Amerikas [conclusion]" type="journal article" year="1935">Hennig (1935)</bibRefCitation>
and then treated as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1922" box="[649,810,1028,1054]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Zelatractodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[649,810,1028,1054]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Zelatractodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation accessDate="2019-07-17" author="Steyskal" box="[859,1050,1028,1055]" firstAuthor="Steyskal" journalOrPublisher="Departamento de Zoologia, Secretaria da Agricultura, Sao Paulo." pageId="86" pageNumber="87" pagination="1 - 33" part="48" publicationUrl="https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/50660619" refId="ref59469" refString="Steyskal G. C. 1968. Family Micropezidae. In: A Catalog of the Diptera of the Americas South of the United States 48: 1 - 33. Departamento de Zoologia, Secretaria da Agricultura, Sao Paulo. Available from https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 50660619 [accessed 17 Jul. 2019]." title="Family Micropezidae" type="journal article" volumeTitle="A Catalog of the Diptera of the Americas South of the United States" year="1968">Steyskal (1968)</bibRefCitation>
. Now that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1922" box="[1185,1346,1028,1054]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Zelatractodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1185,1346,1028,1054]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Zelatractodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[189,329,1064,1089]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Mesoconius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,329,1064,1089]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Mesoconius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are regarded as subjective synonyms, the species described as 
<taxonomicName authority="Schiner, 1864" authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1922" box="[1100,1324,1063,1089]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Tanypoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="garleppi">
<emphasis box="[1100,1324,1063,1089]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Tanypoda garleppi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(until recently treated as 
<taxonomicName authority="Schiner, 1864" authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1922" box="[423,557,1099,1125]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Tanypoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="garleppi">
<emphasis box="[423,557,1099,1125]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Z. garleppi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is a subjective junior homonym and is renamed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marshall" authorityYear="2019" box="[1175,1273,1100,1125]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Mesoconius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ottoi">
<emphasis box="[1175,1273,1100,1125]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">M. ottoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
here. The general habitus and the shape and colour of the frontal vitta suggest a relationship to 
<taxonomicName authority="Marshall, 2019" authorityName="Marshall" authorityYear="2019" box="[1191,1293,1135,1160]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Mesoconius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="garyi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1191,1293,1135,1160]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">M. garyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1301,1394,1134,1160]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, which differs in lacking scutellar bristles, having a dark anterolateral thoracic patch and having a dark frontal vitta that reaches the anterior margin of the frons.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
